{The top seed and the best African, Arab and Egyptian GM, Bassem Amin, was
undisputedly the main contender for the first place. With a double win of both
components of Rapid and Blitz, the overall winner showed there is a reason why
everyone pointed him as the clear favourite. However, turning up to the game
is not sufficient for a win and despite the rather big rating gap "the other
players displayed very good chess and I got in trouble at some point of the
rapid section." (Bassem) Your author didn't discover those troubles and here
is a beautiful example of dynamic play which culminates with an exchange
sacrifice in Petrosian style.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. Nbd2
Nge7 6. Bg2 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h4 h6 10. e5 {Bassem is a frequent
employer of this system which is indeed very suitable for faster time controls.
} a5 11. a4 b6 12. Nb1 (12. Nf1 {-h2-g4 is the standard manoeuvre in this
position but White has set his sights on the b5-square.}) 12... Qc7 13. Bf4 d4
14. Qc1 Kh7 15. Na3 Ba6 16. Nc4 ({I like} 16. g4 $5 {in order to meet} Nd5 {
with} 17. Bg3 {when White can slowly keep building on his impending attack
while it's not clear where Black should seek his counterplay.}) 16... Nd5 17.
Bd2 Rad8 18. h5 Nde7 (18... g5 $1 {would have been even more testing.}) 19. b3
gxh5 ({Also here} 19... g5 {was called for, though} 20. Nxg5+ hxg5 21. Bxg5
Bxc4 22. Be4+ {is a tricky position for Black. Now} Kh8 23. Bf6 $1 {is already
losing, but 22...Nf5 keeps Black in the game.}) 20. Re4 (20. Nh4 $1 Ng6 21. Qd1
$1 {were two power moves that would have seriously placed Black's 19th move in
doubt.}) 20... Ng6 21. Qe1 Nce7 22. Qe2 {A fascinating position in which the
most natural move turns out to be a mistake.} Bb7 (22... Nf5 $1 {would have
prevented White's next move.}) 23. Nh4 $1 {Very elegant. White is ready to
give an exchange on e4, but taking it leads to a deadly attack.} Nf5 (23...
Bxe4 24. Bxe4 Kg8 25. Qxh5 Nxe5 26. Bf4 f6 27. Nxe5 fxe5 28. Bxh6 {is,
materially speaking, not so bad for Black, but positionally it's all over.})
24. Qxh5 Nfxh4 25. Rxh4 $5 Nxh4 26. Qxh4 {Black's main problem is that he
can't bring his pieces to the kingside in order to assist the king.} Rh8 27.
Bg5 Rd5 28. Re1 Kg8 29. Bf6 Bxf6 30. Qxf6 Rh7 31. Nd6 Bc6 32. Be4 Rh8 33. Bxd5
exd5 ({or} 33... Bxd5 34. Ne8 $1) 34. Nf5 {and Black resigned.} 1-0

