{Whenever a trainer complains for lack of material, that should raise a
serious question whether he/she is such a good instructor afterall. The Rapid
games alone are carrying an abundance of examples, as it is the case with this
one. White has a couple of equally good options of continuing the pressure but
which one would you choose?} 31. Qd3 ({I particularly like the backward} 31.
Ng1 Ka7 32. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ge5e6] rerouting the knight to better looking
fields with greener grass and fresher air.}) 31... Kb7 32. Re3 Nf8 33. Qe4+ Ka7
{Could you find a stronger move than} 34. Rd3 {?} (34. b4 $1 {I love the
boldness of this plan, blowing off Black's pawn structure and thus clearing
the way for the knight's jump to d4.} Qxa2 35. e6 Nxe6 36. Qxe6 Rd5 37. Rd3 $18
) 34... Qe7 35. Qc6 Rf7 36. a4 Qe6 37. Qe4 Qf5 {The question is: to exchange
or not the queens?} 38. Qc6 ({Better was} 38. Qxf5 Rxf5 39. Kd2 Kb7 40. Ke3 $16
{[%cal Ge2g3,Gg3e4]}) 38... Qe6 39. Qg2 Rd7 40. Rxd7 Qxd7 41. Qe4 Qg4 42. Nc3
Ne6 43. Nd5 Qxh4 44. Kb2 Qf2 {Subtleties and nuances are hard to spot in rapid
play.} (44... Qd8 $17 {would have prevented White's defensive idea which will
be revealed further on.}) 45. Qxg6 {missing the saving moment.} (45. Ne7 $1 {
where it is Black who is now the one to save the game} Qd4+ 46. Qxd4 Nxd4 47.
c3 Ne6 48. Nxg6 h4 49. f5 h3 50. fxe6 h2 51. e7 h1=Q 52. e8=Q Qg2+ 53. Ka3 Qc2
$11 {followed by perpetual. 'Easy' line, right?:)}) 45... Qd4+ 46. Nc3 Nxf4 47.
Qg7 Nd5 48. Qg3 h4 49. Qd3 Qxc3+ 50. Qxc3 Nxc3 51. Kxc3 Kb7 {The Algerian GM
started as the 2nd favourite after Bassem and finished on the same position in
the Rapid, which gave him some leverage for a less storming 1st Blitz day.} 0-1

